# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: regulatory-compliance
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:regulatory-compliance/alan-mchughen] McHughen served as an Assistant then full Professor and Research Scientist with the University of Saskatchewan from 1982 to 2002.
[src:regulatory-compliance/alan-mchughen] He currently leads the McHughen Research Group at the University of California, Riverside, in the Department of Botany and Plant Sciences.
[src:regulatory-compliance/alan-mchughen] From 2011 to 2012 McHughen served as a Jefferson Science Fellow and Senior Policy Analyst in the Executive Office of the President in the Obama administration.
[src:regulatory-compliance/alan-mchughen] McHughen is a past-President of the International Society for Biosafety Research, a fellow with the American College of Nutrition (2002), a AAAS Fellow with the American Association for the Advancement of Science (2010), and member of the American Society of Plant Biology.
[src:regulatory-compliance/alan-mchughen] McHughen received the Robert Anderson Fellowship in Biochemistry from Yale University and a research fellowship from the Royal Commission for the Exhibition of 1851.
[src:regulatory-compliance/alan-mchughen] He also received the Science in Society Book of the Year Award in 2000 from the Science Writers & Communicators of Canada, the Certificate of Merit from the U.S.
[src:regulatory-compliance/alan-mchughen] Department of Agriculture in 2006, and the Distinguished Lecturer Award from the U.S.
[src:regulatory-compliance/alan-mchughen] Environmental Protection Agency in 2001.
[src:regulatory-compliance/alan-mchughen] McHughen is the author of numerous peer-reviewed research articles, academic papers, and contributor to text books on the issue of genetically modified crops.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:regulatory-compliance/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Anti–money laundering guidelines came into prominence globally as a result of the formation of the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) and the promulgation of an international framework of anti–money laundering standards.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] These standards began to have more relevance in 2000 and 2001, after FATF began a process to publicly identify countries that were deficient in their anti–money laundering laws and international cooperation, a process colloquially known as "name and shame".
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Strict background checks are necessary to combat as many money launderers escape by investing through complex ownership and company structures.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Banks can do that but proper surveillance is required on the government side to reduce this.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Over recent years, the rise in anti–money laundering mechanisms has been attributed to the use of big data and artificial intelligence.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Traditional anti–money laundering systems are falling behind against evolving threats and new technologies are helping AML compliance officers to deal with: poor implementation, expanding regulation, administrative complexity, false positives.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] The elements of the crime of money laundering are set forth in the United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances and Convention against Transnational Organized Crime.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] It is defined as knowingly engaging in a financial transaction with the proceeds of a crime for the purpose of concealing or disguising the illicit origin of the property from governments.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] 1956 and 1957, the two most prominent U.S.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] While banks operating in the same country generally have to follow the same anti–money laundering laws and regulations, financial institutions all structure their anti–money laundering efforts slightly differently.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Today, most financial institutions globally, and many non-financial institutions, are required to identify and report transactions of a suspicious nature to the financial intelligence unit in the respective country.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] For example, a bank must verify a customer's identity and, if necessary, monitor transactions for suspicious activity.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] This process comes under "know your customer" measures, which means knowing the identity of the customer and understanding the kinds of transactions in which the customer is likely to engage.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] By knowing one's customers, financial institutions can often identify unusual or suspicious behaviour, termed anomalies, which may be an indication of money laundering.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Bank employees, such as tellers and customer account representatives, are trained in anti–money laundering and are instructed to report activities that they deem suspicious.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Additionally, anti–money laundering software filters customer data, classifies it according to level of suspicion, and inspects it for anomalies.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Such anomalies include any sudden and substantial increase in funds, a large withdrawal, or moving money to a bank secrecy jurisdiction.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Smaller transactions that meet certain criteria may also be flagged as suspicious.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] For example, structuring can lead to flagged transactions.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] The software also flags names on government "blacklists" and transactions that involve countries hostile to the host nation.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Once the software has mined data and flagged suspect transactions, it alerts bank management, who must then determine whether to file a report with the government.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] The financial services industry has become more vocal about the rising costs of anti–money laundering regulation and the limited benefits that they claim it brings.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] One commentator wrote that "[w]ithout facts, [anti–money laundering] legislation has been driven on rhetoric, driving by ill-guided activism responding to the need to be "seen to be doing something" rather than by an objective understanding of its effects on predicate crime.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] The social panic approach is justified by the language used—we talk of the battle against terrorism or the war on drugs".
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] *The Economist* estimated the annual costs of anti–money laundering efforts in Europe and North America at US$5 billion in 2003, an increase from US$700 million in 2000.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Government-linked economists have noted the significant negative effects of money laundering on economic development, including undermining domestic capital formation, depressing growth, and diverting capital away from development.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Because of the intrinsic uncertainties of the amount of money laundered, changes in the amount of money laundered, and the cost of anti–money laundering systems, it is almost impossible to tell which anti–money laundering systems work and which are more or less cost effective.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Besides economic costs to implement anti–money-laundering laws, improper attention to data protection practices may entail disproportionate costs to individual privacy rights.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] In June 2011, the data-protection advisory committee to the European Union issued a report on data protection issues related to the prevention of money laundering and terrorist financing, which identified numerous transgressions against the established legal framework on privacy and data protection.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] The report made recommendations on how to address money laundering and terrorist financing in ways that safeguard personal privacy rights and data protection laws.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] In the United States, groups such as the American Civil Liberties Union have expressed concern that money laundering rules require banks to report on their own customers, essentially conscripting private businesses "into agents of the surveillance state".
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Mexico, which has faced a significant increase in violent crime, established anti–money laundering controls in 2013 to curb the underlying crime issue.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Formed in 1989 by the G7 countries, the Financial Action Task Force on Money Laundering (FATF) is an intergovernmental body whose purpose is to develop and promote an international response to combat money laundering.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] The FATF Secretariat is housed at the headquarters of the OECD in Paris.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] In October 2001, FATF expanded its mission to include combating the financing of terrorism.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] FATF is a policy-making body that brings together legal, financial, and law enforcement experts to achieve national legislation and regulatory AML and CFT reforms.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] As of 2014 its membership consists of 36 countries and territories and two regional organizations.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] FATF works in collaboration with a number of international bodies and organizations.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] These entities have observer status with FATF, which does not entitle them to vote, but permits them full participation in plenary sessions and working groups.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] FATF has developed 40 recommendations on money laundering and 9 special recommendations regarding terrorist financing.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] FATF assesses each member country against these recommendations in published reports.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Countries seen as not being sufficiently compliant with such recommendations are subjected to financial sanctions.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] Promoting the adoption and implementation of FATF anti–money laundering standards globally.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] The FATF currently comprises 34 member jurisdictions and 2 regional organisations, representing most major financial centres in all parts of the globe.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] The United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime maintains the *International Money Laundering Information Network*, a website that provides information and software for anti–money laundering data collection and analysis.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] The World Bank has a website that provides policy advice and best practices to governments and the private sector on anti–money laundering issues.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p01] The Basel AML Index is an independent annual ranking that assesses the risk of money laundering and terrorist financing around the world.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Many jurisdictions adopt a list of specific predicate crimes for money laundering prosecutions, while others criminalize the proceeds of any serious crimes.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The Financial Transactions and Reports Analysis Center of Afghanistan (FinTRACA) was established as a Financial Intelligence Unit under the Anti Money Laundering and Proceeds of Crime Law passed by decree late in 2004.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The main purpose of this law is to protect the integrity of the Afghan financial system and to gain compliance with international treaties and conventions.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The Financial Intelligence Unit is a semi-independent body that is administratively housed within the Central Bank of Afghanistan (Da Afghanistan Bank).
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The main objective of FinTRACA is to deny the use of the Afghan financial system to those who obtained funds as the result of illegal activity, and to those who would use it to support terrorist activities.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] To meet its objectives, the FinTRACA collects and analyzes information from a variety of sources.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] These sources include entities with legal obligations to submit reports to the FinTRACA when a suspicious activity is detected, as well as reports of cash transactions above a threshold amount specified by regulation.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Also, FinTRACA has access to all related Afghan government information and databases.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] When the analysis of this information supports the supposition of illegal use of the financial system, the FinTRACA works closely with law enforcement to investigate and prosecute the illegal activity.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] FinTRACA also cooperates internationally in support of its own analyses and investigations and to support the analyses and investigations of foreign counterparts, to the extent allowed by law.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Other functions include training of those entities with legal obligations to report information, development of laws and regulations to support national-level AML objectives, and international and regional cooperation in the development of AML typologies and countermeasures.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] After the Taliban regained control of the country in August 2021, FinTRACA's access to international financial intelligence data was removed.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] As of April 2026, access has not been re-established.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] To ensure the existence of legal mechanisms necessary for the stability of Armenian economy, the government set up a Financial Monitoring Center (FMC).
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The Financial Monitoring Center of Armenia is a financial intelligence unit of an administrative type and is situated in the Central Bank of Armenia.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The center proposed and adopted the Law of the Republic of Armenia on fight against Legalizing the Illegal Incomes and Financing of Terrorism.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] This Law is based on the FATF 40 Recommendations, model laws and best international practices.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The law is intended to protect the rights, freedoms and legal interests of the citizens, society, and the state, as well as to ensure the existence of legal mechanisms necessary for the stability of economic system of the Republic of Armenia.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Australia has adopted a number of strategies to combat money laundering, which mirror those of a majority of western countries.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The Attorney-General's Department maintains a list of outlawed terror organisations.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] It is an offense to materially support or be supported by such organisations.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] It is an offence to open a bank account in Australia in a false name, and rigorous procedures must be followed when new bank accounts are opened.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The *Anti–Money Laundering and Counter–Terrorism Financing Act 2006* (Cth) (AML/CTF Act) is the principal legislative instrument, although there are also offence provisions contained in Division 400 of the *Criminal Code Act 1995* (Cth).
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The *Proceeds of Crime Act 2002* (Cth) imposes criminal penalties on a person who engages in money laundering.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The organized criminal groups in Albania had long been involved in several illicit activities, including drug trade, arms and human trafficking, kidnapping, murders and others.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Such criminals were attracted to the United Arab Emirates to seek refuge and to launder their illegal wealth.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The UAE lacked regulations to combat the issue of terror funding and money laundering.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Consequently, it became a safe haven for criminals from Albania and other Balkan countries, who escaped justice and continued to carry out their illegal activities while living in the Emirates.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] For countries like Albania, the complications were greater, due to the lack of bilateral extradition treaty with the UAE.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Authorities in Albania struggled and failed to get most of the criminals extradited from the Emirates.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Usually, the Gulf nation doesn't refuse to extradite these criminals, but it used to extend the process to the point of their release.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The first anti–money laundering legislation in Bangladesh was the *Money Laundering Prevention Act, 2002*.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] It was replaced by the *Money Laundering Prevention Ordinance 2008*.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Subsequently, the ordinance was repealed by the *Money Laundering Prevention Act, 2009*.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] To prevent these Illegal uses of money, the Bangladesh government has introduced the Money Laundering Prevention Act.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The Act was last amended in the year 2009 and all the financial institutes are following this act.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Till today there are 26 circulars issued by Bangladesh Bank under this act.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] In 2000, the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) Act was amended to expand the scope of its application and to establish a financial intelligence unit with national control over money laundering, namely FINTRAC.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] In December 2001, the scope of the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) Act was again expanded by amendments enacted under the Anti-Terrorism Act with the objective of deterring terrorist activity by cutting off sources and channels of funding used by terrorists in response to 9/11.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) Act was renamed the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] In December 2006, the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act was further amended, in part, in response to pressure from the FATF for Canada to tighten its money laundering and financing of terrorism legislation.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The amendments also enabled greater money laundering and terrorist financial intelligence sharing among enforcement agencies.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] However, in recent years, casinos and realtors have been embroiled in scandal for aiding and abetting money launderers, especially in Vancouver, which has come to be known as the "Vancouver Model".
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Some have speculated that approximately $1 Billion is laundered in Vancouver per year.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] In 2024, China’s supreme court and chief prosecutor jointly issued the Interpretation of Several Issues Concerning the Application of Law in Handling Criminal Cases of Money Laundering (2024).
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] In American and British English, this title would translate to Money Laundering Prosecution Guidelines, and they explain how Criminal Law act section 191 applies to money laundering proceeds from specific unlawful activities.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The fourth iteration of the EU's anti–money laundering directive (AMLD IV) was published on 5 June 2015, after clearing its last legislative stop at the European Parliament.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] This directive brought the EU's money laundering laws more in line with the US's, which is advantageous for financial institutions operating in both jurisdictions.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The Fifth Money Laundering Directive (5MLD) came into force on 10 January 2020, addressing a number of weaknesses in the European Union's AML/CFT regime that came to light after the enactment of the Fourth Money Laundering Directive AMLD IV).
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The AMLD5 increased the scope of the EU's AML regulations.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] It decreased the threshold of customer identity verification for the prepaid card industry from EUR 250 to EUR 150.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The customers who deposit or transfer funds more than EUR150 will be identified by the prepaid card issuing company.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Lack of harmonization in AML requirements between the US and EU has complicated the compliance efforts of global institutions that are looking to standardize the Know Your Customer (KYC) component of their AML programs across key jurisdictions.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] AMLD IV promises to better align the AML regimes by adopting a more risk-based approach compared to its predecessor, AMLD III.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Certain components of the directive, however, go beyond current requirements in both the EU and US, imposing new implementation challenges on banks.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] For instance, more public officials are brought within the scope of the directive, and EU member states are required to establish new registries of "beneficial owners" (i.e., those who ultimately own or control each company) which will impact banks.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] On 24 January 2019, the European Commission sent official warnings to ten member states as part of a crackdown on lax application of money laundering regulations.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The Commission sent Germany a letter of formal notice, the first step of the EU legal procedure against states.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Belgium, Finland, France, Lithuania, and Portugal were sent reasoned opinions, the second step of the procedure which could lead to fines.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] A second round of reasoned opinions was sent to Bulgaria, Cyprus, Poland, and Slovakia.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The ten countries have two months to respond or face court action.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The commission had set a 26 June 2017 deadline for EU countries to apply new rules against money laundering and terrorist financing.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] On 13 February 2019, the Commission added Saudi Arabia, Panama, Nigeria and other jurisdictions to a blacklist of nations that pose a threat because of lax controls on terrorism financing and money laundering.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] This is a more expansive list than that of FATF.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] In 2024, the European Union established the Anti-Money Laundering Authority, an EU-level agency intended to centralize aspects of AML enforcement in the EU and foster better coordination among national financial intelligence units.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The 6th Anti-Money Laundering Directive must be incorporated into national law by July 10, 2027.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] In 2002, the Parliament of India passed an act called the Prevention of Money Laundering Act, 2002.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The main objectives of this act are to prevent money-laundering as well as to provide for confiscation of property either derived from or involved in, money-laundering.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] (a) Maintain records that detail the nature and value of transactions, whether such transactions comprise a single transaction or a series of connected transactions, and where these transactions take place within a month.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] (b) Furnish information on transactions referred to in clause (a) to the Director within the time prescribed, including records of the identity of all its clients.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Section 12 (2) prescribes that the records referred to in sub-section (1) as mentioned above, must be maintained for ten years after the transactions finished.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] It is handled by the Indian Income Tax Department.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The provisions of the Act are frequently reviewed and various amendments have been passed from time to time.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Most money laundering activities in India are through political parties, corporate companies and the share market.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] These are investigated by the Enforcement Directorate and Indian Income Tax Department.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] According to Government of India, out of the total tax arrears of ₹2,480 billion (US$26 billion) about ₹1,300 billion (US$14 billion) pertain to money laundering and securities scam cases.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Bank accountants must record all transactions over Rs.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] 1 million and maintain such records for 10 years.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Banks must also make cash transaction reports (CTRs) and suspicious transaction reports over Rs.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] 1 million within 7 days of initial suspicion.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] They must submit their reports to the Enforcement Directorate and Income Tax Department.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] To combat money laundering, the Economic and Financial Crimes Commission was established in 2003.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] This body works alongside the Central Bank of Nigeria and the National Drug Law Enforcement Agency, to investigate and prosecute, individuals charged with the crime.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The Money laundering Act was also established in 2011.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] This act contains elaborate provisions on the legal and institutional framework to prevent money laundering.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The act also established the Special Control Unit against Money Laundering, under the EFCC.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The act also states that all agents acting on behalf of customers must be fully identified and verified.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] It also established that the source of wealth of political persons must be investigated and identified.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Other measures have been taken by the government to prevent money laundering.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] In May 2022, President Muhammadu Buhari signed into law three bills.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] These bills are; Money laundering (Prevention and Prohibition bill), 2022, the Terrorism (Prevention and Prohibition bill) 2022, and the Proceeds of Crime (Recovery and Management) Bill, 2022.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The Central Bank of Nigeria also listed Regulations to prevent Money laundering in Nigeria.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The Apex bank stated that all transactions conducted through correspondent banking relationships shall be managed with a risk-based approach and Know Your Correspondent procedures, this is to ascertain whether the bank or financial institution is regulated by a money laundering prevention body.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The correspondent is to take action to identify the customer.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The CBN also released a guidance note named; Anti–money Laundering/combating the financing of terrorism (AML/CFT) for OFIs.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The CBN Financial Policy and Regulation Director Chibuzo Efobi mentioned that the guidance note would enable the sub-sector to identify, assess and minimize the risks of terrorist financing and money laundering.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] He also said that this Guidance note would identify risk management procedures that would lessen the vulnerability of financial institutions to Money laundering schemes.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] There is a relationship between corruption and money laundering in developing countries.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The economic power of Latin America increases rapidly and without support, these fortunes being of illicit origin having the appearance of legally acquired profits.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] With regard to money laundering, the ultimate goal of the process is to integrate illicit capital into the general economy and transform it into licit goods and services.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] The money laundering practice uses various channels to legalize everything achieved through illegal practices.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Casinos continue to attract organizations that deal with money laundering.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p02] Aruba and the Netherlands Antilles, the Cayman Islands, Colombia, Mexico, Panama and Venezuela are considered high priority countries in the region, due to the strategies used by the washers.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The practice of money laundering, among other economic and financial crimes seeps into the economic and political structures of most developing countries therefore resulting to political instability and economic digression.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Money laundering is still a great concern for the financial services industry.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] About 50% of the money laundering incidents in Latin America were reported by organizations in the financial sector.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] According to PwC's 2014 global economic crime survey, in Latin America only 2.8% of respondents in Latin America claimed suffering Antitrust/Competition Law incidents, compared to 5.2% of respondents globally.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] It has been shown that money laundering has an impact on the financial behavior and macroeconomic performance of the industrialized countries.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] In these countries the macroeconomic consequences of money laundering are transmitted through several channels.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Thus, money laundering complicates the formulation of economic policies.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] It is assumed that the proceeds of criminal activities are laundered by means of the notes and coins in circulation of the monetary substitutes.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The laundering causes disproportionate changes in the relative prices of assets which implies that resources are allocated inefficiently; and, therefore may have negative implications for economic growth, apparently money laundering is associated with a lower economic growth.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The Office of National Drug Control Policy of the United States estimates that only in that country, sales of narcotic drugs represent about 57,000 million dollars annually and most of these transactions are made in cash.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The term 'money laundering' is not used as such within the CDSA.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] In South Africa, the Financial Intelligence Centre Act (2001) and subsequent amendments have added responsibilities to the Financial Intelligence Centre (FIC) to combat money laundering.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The United Arab Emirates has long been known as a hub of illicit financial flows and corruption.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] A large number business, real estate and financial transactions of the country majorly involve some sort of illegal activity.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Moreover, several corrupt and criminal actors from across the world operate through or from the Emirates, including European money launderers, Nigerian kleptocrats, East African gold smugglers, Afghan warlords and others.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Even the royal family members of the UAE are often known to be associated with certain cases of offshore holdings.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] However, in 2022, the UAE fell into a risk of being named in the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) "grey list".
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The list defines nations determined to have "strategic deficiencies" in combating money laundering and terrorist financing.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] On 4 March 2022, FATF placed the UAE in its 'grey' list of countries that are subject to increased monitoring.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] In April 2020, the Emirates had been warned of its money laundering activities, where FATF called the UAE's limited prosecutions on the issue a "concern".
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] In November 2021, the group received a report from the Emirates, which did not reach much of the thresholds required for avoid the grey list.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] A report in June 2023 revealed that the Western countries, including Germany, Italy, Greece and the U.S., had been pushing FATF to remove the UAE from its grey list on money laundering, despite the Emirates’ image of being a haven for illicit flows.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Members of FATF’s International Cooperation Review Group (ICRG) raised concerns that the UAE overpromised, but undelivered.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] However, ICRG’s representatives from the U.S. and European allies refused to address such concerns.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] A study by Swissaid revealed that 93% of undeclared African gold ended up in the UAE, making it the leading importer of smuggled gold from the continent.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] A co-author of the report, Marc Ummel said the FATF should reconsider the February 2024 removal of the Emirates from its “grey list”, as the country was illegally importing gold from Africa.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] He pointed out that the African gold is majorly linked to conflict, money laundering and human rights issues, leaving people extracting gold with nothing.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The Kinahan brothers are sons of the Kinahan Cartel founder, Christy Kinahan Senior, who smuggled drugs and firearms into the UK, Ireland, and mainland Europe for long.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] For several years, the Kinahan leadership had been residing in Dubai, where Daniel denied his involvement in organized crime by defending himself as a ‘high-profile businessman in the professional boxing industry'.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] According to Panorama investigation, Daniel has operated in the boxing industry through MTK and simultaneously operated Europe's biggest money laundering, drug trafficking, and gangland executions networks from Dubai.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] A spokesperson for minister O'Brien said, "respect for human rights is a cornerstone of Ireland's foreign policy," when asked if the minister would raise the concerns regarding Daniel's presence and operations in Dubai on his visit in March 2022 for St Patrick's Day.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The European Union placed the UAE on its money laundering blacklist, in December 2022.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] It implied that the EU considers the Emirates a high-risk nation that presents "strategic deficiencies in the anti–money laundering countering the financing of terrorism regimes".
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The move was taken amid the conflict against the Kinahan Organised Crime Group (KOCG), and was expected to push the authorities to take proactive measures against members of the Kinahan cartel.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] In July 2025, the European Commission revised its list of high-risk jurisdictions for money laundering and terrorism financing, which excluded the UAE.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The European Parliament voted in favor of the updated list, which was earlier opposed by the MEPs.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The decision to remove the Emirates from the EU money laundering blacklist was criticized by Transparency International, which said the country’s reforms cannot be considered effective yet.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The EU listing process also came into question for not allowing the Parliament to assess the countries individually.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Lawmakers and civil society groups also condemned the delisting, stating that the decision is politically motivated and submits to geopolitical pressure.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] In September 2025, several UAE-based individuals, companies and front companies were sanctioned by the US Treasury for supporting the IRGC and Iran's Ministry of Defense and Armed Forces Logistics (MODAFL).
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The sanctioned entities and individuals were part of an Iranian “shadow banking” network, exploiting international financial system and evading sanctions by laundering money through cryptocurrency and overseas front companies.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The UAE-based firms that faced sanctions included Alpa Trading – FZCO, Alpa Investment L.L.C, and other front companies that facilitated illegal money flows.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] As a result of the sanctions, all property related to the designated individuals in the US is blocked, while the US citizens are prohibited from conducting transactions with them.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Money Laundering Regulations are designed to protect the UK financial system, as well as preventing and detecting crime.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] If a business is covered by these regulations then controls are put in place to prevent it being used for money laundering.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Money laundering is broadly defined in the UK.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] In effect any handling or involvement with any proceeds of any crime (or monies or assets representing the proceeds of crime) can be a money laundering offence.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] An offender's possession of the proceeds of his own crime falls within the UK definition of money laundering.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The definition also covers activities within the traditional definition of money laundering, as a process that conceals or disguises the proceeds of crime to make them appear legitimate.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Unlike certain other jurisdictions (notably the US and much of Europe), UK money laundering offences are not limited to the proceeds of serious crimes, nor are there any monetary limits.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Financial transactions need no money laundering design or purpose for UK laws to consider them a money laundering offence.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] A money laundering offence under UK legislation need not even involve money, since the money laundering legislation covers assets of any description.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] In consequence, any person who commits an acquisitive crime (i.e., one that produces some benefit in the form of money or an asset of any description) in the UK inevitably also commits a money laundering offence under UK legislation.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] This applies also to a person who, by criminal conduct, evades a liability (such as a taxation liability)—which lawyers call "obtaining a pecuniary advantage"—as he is deemed thereby to obtain a sum of money equal in value to the liability evaded.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The principal money laundering offences carry a maximum penalty of 14 years' imprisonment.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Secondary regulation is provided by the Money Laundering Regulations 2003, which were replaced by the Money Laundering Regulations 2007.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] They are directly based on the EU Directives 91/308/EEC, 2001/97/EC and (through the 2007 regulations) 2005/60/EC.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The regulations list a number of supervisory authorities who have a role in overseeing the financial activities of their members.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] In most circumstances it would be an offence, "tipping-off", for the reporter to inform the subject of his report that a report has been made.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] These provisions do not however require disclosure to the authorities of information received by certain professionals in privileged circumstances or where the information is subject to legal professional privilege.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Others that are subject to these regulations include financial institutions, credit institutions, estate agents (which includes chartered surveyors), trust and company service providers, high value dealers (who accept cash equivalent to €15,000 or more for goods sold), and casinos.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Professional guidance (which is submitted to and approved by the UK Treasury) is provided by industry groups including the Joint Money Laundering Steering Group, the Law Society. and the Consultative Committee of Accountancy Bodies (CCAB).
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] However, there is no obligation on banking institutions to routinely report monetary deposits or transfers above a specified value.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Instead reports must be made of all suspicious deposits or transfers, irrespective of their value.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The reporting obligations include reporting suspicious gains from conduct in other countries that would be criminal if it took place in the UK.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Exceptions were later added for certain activities legal where they took place, such as bullfighting in Spain.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] More than 200,000 reports of suspected money laundering are submitted annually to authorities in the UK (there were 240,582 reports in the year ended 30 September 2010.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] This was an increase from the 228,834 reports submitted in the previous year).
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Most of these reports are submitted by banks and similar financial institutions (there were 186,897 reports from the banking sector in the year ended 30 September 2010).
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Although 5,108 different organisations submitted suspicious activity reports to the authorities in the year ended 30 September 2010, just four organisations submitted approximately half of all reports, and the top 20 reporting organisations accounted for three-quarters of all reports.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The offence of failing to report a suspicion of money laundering by another person carries a maximum penalty of five years' imprisonment.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The Criminal Finances Act 2017 introduced unexplained wealth orders, another tool to combat money laundering, whereby the owner of an asset greater than £50,000 may be required to show how the purchase was financed.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The legislation was passed by the House of Lords on 21 May and received Royal Asset on 23 May.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] However, the Act's public register provision is facing legal challenges from local governments in the Cayman Islands and British Virgin Islands, who argue that it violates their Constitutional sovereignty.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Under the Proceeds of Crime Act goods that criminals cannot legally account for are seized and sold at auction to raise funds.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] This is usually carried out by authorised auction houses and often within the geographical areas of the criminals.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] All UK *Bureaux de change* are registered with His Majesty's Revenue and Customs, which issues a trading licence for each location.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Bureaux de change and money transmitters, such as Western Union outlets, in the UK fall within the "regulated sector" and are required to comply with the Money Laundering Regulations 2007.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Checks can be carried out by HMRC on all Money Service Businesses.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] It also threatened that these countries could be blacklisted, if they failed to meet the regulatory standards.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] This was LBMA's first move to challenge the illegal or unethical production and trading of gold.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] A former partner of the UK-based accounting firm Ernst & Young, Amjad Rihan was ousted after he attempted to report the money laundering and gold smuggling efforts of Dubai-based firm Kaloti Jewellery International.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Rihan had claimed that "Kaloti was knowingly dealing in gold bullion smuggled out of Morocco".
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] However, after he reported the issue, the Dubai government body, DMCC, attempted to put unnecessary pressure on him and his firm.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] In 2021, Ernst & Young withdrew an eight-year-long legal fight against Rihan asking a compensation of $10.8 million from him.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The approach in the United States to stop money laundering is usually broken into two areas: preventive (regulatory) measures, and prosecutorial measures.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] In the United States, whistleblowers can report money laundering activities to the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) or the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) if the case also implicates a security.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] In an attempt to prevent dirty money from entering the U.S. financial system in the first place, the United States Congress passed a series of laws, starting in 1970, collectively known as the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA).
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Cash transactions in excess of a certain amount must be reported on a currency transaction report (CTR), identifying the individual making the transaction as well as the source of the cash.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The law originally required all transactions of US$5,000 or more to be reported, but due to excessively high levels of reporting the threshold was raised to US$10,000.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The U.S. is one of the few countries in the world to require reporting of all cash transactions over a certain limit, although certain businesses can be exempt from the requirement.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Attempts by customers to circumvent the BSA, generally by structuring cash deposits to amounts lower than US$10,000 by breaking them up and depositing them on different days or at different locations also violates the law.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The financial database created by these reports is administered by the U.S.'s Financial Intelligence Unit, called the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN), located in Vienna, Virginia.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The reports are made available to U.S. criminal investigators, as well as other FIU's around the globe, and FinCEN conducts computer-assisted analyses of these reports to determine trends and refer investigations.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The BSA requires financial institutions to engage in customer due diligence, or KYC, which is sometimes known in parlance as know your customer.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] It includes obtaining satisfactory identification to assure that the account is in the customer's actual name and understanding the expected nature and source of the money that flows through the customer's accounts.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Other customers, such as those with private banking accounts and those of foreign government officials, are subjected to enhanced due diligence because the law deems that those accounts are at a higher risk for money laundering.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] All accounts are subject to ongoing monitoring, in which internal bank software scrutinizes transactions and flags for manual inspection those that fall outside specific parameters.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] If a manual inspection reveals that the transaction is suspicious, the institution should file a Suspicious Activity Report.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The regulators of the industries involved are responsible to ensure that the financial institutions comply with the BSA.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] For example, the Federal Reserve and the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency regularly inspect banks, and may impose civil fines or refer matters for criminal prosecution for non-compliance.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] A number of banks have been fined and prosecuted for failure to comply with the BSA.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Most famously, Riggs Bank, in Washington D.C., was prosecuted and functionally driven out of business as a result of its failure to apply proper money laundering controls, particularly as it related to foreign political figures.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] In addition to the BSA, the U.S. imposes controls on the movement of currency across its borders, requiring individuals to report the transportation of cash in excess of US$10,000 on a form called Report of International Transportation of Currency or Monetary Instruments (known as a CMIR).
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Likewise, businesses, such as automobile dealerships, that receive cash in excess of US$10,000 must file a Form 8300 with the Internal Revenue Service, identifying the source of the cash.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] On 1 September 2010, the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network issued an advisory on "informal value transfer systems" referencing *United States v.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] In the United States, there are perceived consequences of anti–money laundering (AML) regulations.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] These unintended consequences include FinCEN's publishing of a list of "risky businesses", which many believe unfairly targeted money service businesses.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The publishing of this list and the subsequent fall-out, banks indiscriminately de-risking MSBs, is referred to as Operation Choke Point.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The Financial Crimes Enforcement Network issued a Geographic Targeting Order to combat illegal money laundering in the United States.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] This means that title insurance companies in the U.S. are required to identify the natural persons behind companies that pay all cash in residential real estate purchases over a particular amount in certain U.S. cities.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The Corporate Transparency Act (CTA) is a significant piece of legislation in the United States aimed at combating money laundering and enhancing financial transparency.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Enacted as part of the National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2021, the CTA mandates that corporations, limited liability companies (LLCs), and similar entities disclose information about their beneficial owners to the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN).
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] This requirement is designed to help authorities identify and track individuals who control or profit from these entities, thereby closing loopholes often exploited for illicit activities.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The CTA requires entities to file Beneficial Ownership Information (BOI) reports with FinCEN.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] These reports must include details such as the names, addresses, dates of birth, and identification numbers of the beneficial owners.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] By gathering this information, the CTA aims to create a comprehensive database that federal, state, and local law enforcement agencies can access to investigate and prevent financial crimes.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The legislation reflects a broader international effort to enhance corporate transparency and ensure that entities cannot be used to hide illicit funds or conduct illegal activities anonymously.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Money laundering has been criminalized in the United States since the Money Laundering Control Act of 1986.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The law, contained at section 1956 of Title 18 of the United States Code, prohibits individuals from engaging in a financial transaction with proceeds that were generated from certain specific crimes, known as "specified unlawful activities" (SUAs).
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The law requires that an individual specifically intends to make the transaction to conceal the source, ownership or control of the funds.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] There is no minimum threshold of money and no requirement that the transaction succeeded in actually disguising the money.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] A "financial transaction" has been broadly defined, and need not involve a financial institution, or even a business.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Merely passing money from one person to another, with the intent to disguise the source, ownership, location or control of the money, has been deemed a financial transaction under the law.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The possession of money without either a financial transaction or an intent to conceal is not a crime in the United States.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Besides money laundering, the law contained in section 1957 of Title 18 of the United States Code, prohibits spending more than US$10,000 derived from an SUA, regardless of whether the individual wishes to disguise it.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] It carries a lesser penalty than money laundering, and unlike the money laundering statute, requires that the money pass through a financial institution.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] According to the records compiled by the United States Sentencing Commission, in 2009, the United States Department of Justice typically convicted a little over 81,000 people; of this, approximately 800 were convicted of money laundering as the primary or most serious charge.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988 expanded the definition of financial institution to include businesses such as car dealers and real estate closing personnel and required them to file reports on large currency transactions.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] It required verification of identity of those who purchase monetary instruments over $3,000.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] HIFCA zones may be defined geographically or can be created to address money laundering in an industry sector, a financial institution, or group of financial institutions.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] The gaming and gambling industry has increasingly adopted anti-money laundering (AML) technologies in response to evolving regulatory expectations and the growing complexity of digital transactions.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] Online casinos and gaming platforms often operate with virtual currencies, microtransactions, and peer-to-peer trading systems, which require enhanced oversight to ensure financial transparency.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] To address these challenges, many operators have implemented advanced compliance measures such as Know Your Customer (KYC) procedures, real-time transaction monitoring, and AI-driven behavioral analytics.
[src:regulatory-compliance/anti-money-laundering-p03] These technologies assist in identifying irregular activity, supporting regulatory compliance, and reinforcing the integrity of financial operations within the sector.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Auditors consider the propositions before them, obtain evidence, document their findings, and evaluate the propositions in their auditing report.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Audits provide third-party assurance to various stakeholders that the subject matter is free from material misstatement.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] The term is most frequently applied to audits of the financial information relating to a legal person.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Other commonly audited areas include: secretarial and compliance, internal controls, quality management, project management, water management, and energy conservation.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] As a result of an audit, stakeholders may evaluate and improve the effectiveness of risk management, control, and governance over the subject matter.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] In recent years auditing has expanded to encompass many areas of public and corporate life.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Professor Michael Power refers to this extension of auditing practices as the "Audit Society".
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] The word "audit" derives from the Latin word *audire* which means "to hear".
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Auditing has been a safeguard measure since ancient times.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] During medieval times, when manual bookkeeping was prevalent, auditors in Britain used to hear the accounts read out for them and checked that the organization's personnel were not negligent or fraudulent.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] In 1951, Moyer identified that the most important duty of the auditor was to detect fraud.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Chatfield documented that early United States auditing was viewed mainly as verification of bookkeeping detail.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] The Central Auditing Commission of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union (Russian: Центральная ревизионная комиссия КПСС) operated from 1921 to 1990.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] An **information technology audit**, or **information systems audit**, is an examination of the management controls within an Information technology (IT) infrastructure.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] The evaluation of obtained evidence determines if the information systems are safeguarding assets, maintaining data integrity, and operating effectively to achieve the organization's goals or objectives.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] These reviews may be performed in conjunction with a financial statement audit, internal audit, or other form of attestation engagement.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Due to strong incentives (including taxation, misselling and other forms of fraud) to misstate financial information, auditing has become a legal requirement for many entities who have the power to exploit financial information for personal gain.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Traditionally, audits were mainly associated with gaining information about financial systems and the financial records of a company or a business.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Financial audits also assess whether a business or corporation adheres to legal duties as well as other applicable statutory customs and regulations.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Financial audits are performed to ascertain the validity and reliability of information, as well as to provide an assessment of a system's internal control.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] The third party auditor will express an opinion of the person, organization, or system in question.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] The opinion given on financial statements will depend on the audit evidence obtained.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] A statutory audit is a legally required review of the accuracy of a company's or government's financial statements and records.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] The purpose of a statutory audit is to determine whether an organization provides a fair and accurate representation of its financial position by examining information such as bank balances, bookkeeping records, and financial transactions.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Due to constraints, an audit seeks to provide only **reasonable assurance** that the statements are free from material error.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Hence, statistical sampling is often adopted in audits.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] In the case of financial audits, a set of financial statements are said to be true and fair when they are free of material misstatements – a concept influenced by both quantitative (numerical) and qualitative factors.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Recently, the argument that auditing should go beyond just true and fair is gaining momentum, and the US Public Company Accounting Oversight Board has come out with a concept release on the same.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Cost accounting is a process for verifying the cost of manufacturing or producing of any article, on the basis of accounts measuring the use of material, labor or other items of cost.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] The term "cost audit" refers to a systematic and accurate verification of the cost accounts and records, and checking for adherence to the cost accounting objectives.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] In most nations, an audit must adhere to generally accepted standards established by governing bodies.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] These standards assure third parties or external users that they can rely upon the auditor's opinion on the fairness of financial statements or other subjects on which the auditor expresses an opinion.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] The audit must therefore be precise and accurate, containing no additional misstatements or errors.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] In the US, audits of publicly traded companies are governed by rules laid down by the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (PCAOB), which was established by Section 404 of the Sarbanes–Oxley Act of 2002.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Such an audit is called an integrated audit, where auditors, in addition to an opinion on the financial statements, must also express an opinion on the *effectiveness* of a company's *internal control* over financial reporting, in accordance with PCAOB Auditing Standard No.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] There are also new types of integrated auditing becoming available that use unified compliance material (see the unified compliance section in Regulatory compliance).
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Due to the increasing number of regulations and need for operational transparency, organizations are adopting risk-based audits that can cover multiple regulations and standards from a single audit event.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] This is a very new approach in some sectors to ensure that all the necessary governance requirements can be met without duplicating effort from both audit and audit hosting resources.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] The purpose of an assessment is to measure something or calculate a value for it.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] An auditor's objective is to determine whether financial statements are presented fairly, in all material respects, and are free of material misstatement.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Although the process of producing an assessment may involve an audit by an independent professional, its purpose is to provide a measurement rather than to express an opinion about the fairness of statements or quality of performance.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] The most commonly used external audit standards are the US GAAS of the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants and the International Standards on Auditing (ISA) developed by the International Auditing and Assurance Standard.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Recent advances in artificial intelligence and automation are reshaping audit practice.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Audit firms now apply data analytics and machine-learning techniques to analyze entire datasets instead of statistical samples, improving anomaly detection and efficiency.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] However, these technologies also introduce challenges related to data quality, algorithmic bias, and the need for professional judgment.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] A performance audit is an independent examination of a program, function, operation or the management systems and procedures of a governmental or non-profit entity to assess whether the entity is achieving economy, efficiency and effectiveness in the employment of available resources.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Safety, security, information systems performance, and environmental concerns are increasingly the subject of audits.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] There are now audit professionals who specialize in security audits and information systems audits.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] With nonprofit organizations and government agencies, there has been an increasing need for performance audits, examining their success in satisfying mission objectives.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Quality audits are performed to verify conformance to standards through reviewing objective evidence.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] A system of quality audits may verify the effectiveness of a quality management system.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] This is part of certifications such as ISO 9001.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Quality audits are essential to verify the existence of objective evidence showing conformance to required processes, to assess how successfully processes have been implemented, and to judge the effectiveness of achieving any defined target levels.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Quality audits are also necessary to provide evidence concerning reduction and elimination of problem areas, and they are a hands-on management tool for achieving continual improvement in an organization.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] To benefit the organization, quality auditing should not only report non-conformance and corrective actions but also highlight areas of good practice and provide evidence of conformance.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] In this way, other departments may share information and amend their working practices as a result, also enhancing continual improvement.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] A project audit provides an opportunity to uncover issues, concerns and challenges encountered during the project lifecycle.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Conducted midway through the project, a project audit provides the project manager, project sponsor and project team an interim view of what has gone well, as well as what needs to be improved to successfully complete the project.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] If done at the close of a project, the audit can be used to develop success criteria for future projects by providing a forensic review.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] This review identifies which elements of the project were successfully managed and which ones presented challenges.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] As a result, the review will help the organization identify what it needs to do to avoid repeating the same mistakes on future projects.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] An energy audit is an inspection, survey and analysis of energy flows for energy conservation in a building, process or system to reduce the amount of energy input into the system without negatively affecting the output.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] An operations audit is an examination of the operations of the client's business.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] In this audit, the auditor thoroughly examines the efficiency, effectiveness and economy of the operations with which the management of the client is achieving its objectives.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] The operational audit goes beyond internal controls issues since management does not achieve its objectives merely by compliance to a satisfactory system of internal controls.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Operational audits cover any matters which may be commercially unsound.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] The objective of operational audit is to examine three E's, namely: Effectiveness – doing the right things with the least wastage of resources, Efficiency – performing work in the least possible time, and Economy – balance between benefits and costs to run the operation.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] A control self-assessment is a commonly used tool for completing an operations audit.
[src:regulatory-compliance/audit] Also referred to as forensic accountancy, forensic accountant or forensic accounting, a forensic audit is an investigative audit in which accountants specialized in both accounting and investigation seek to uncover frauds, missing money and negligence.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The **Australian Communications and Media Authority** (**ACMA**) is an Australian government statutory authority within the Communications portfolio.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] ACMA was formed on 1 July 2005 with the merger of the Australian Broadcasting Authority and the Australian Communications Authority.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] ACMA is responsible for collecting broadcasting, radiocommunication and telecommunication taxes, and regulating Australian media.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] It does this through various legislation, regulations, standards and codes of practice.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] ACMA is a converged regulator, created to oversee the convergence of telecommunications, broadcasting, radio communications and the internet.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] ACMA is an independent government agency managed by an executive team comprising the Chair (who is also the Agency Head), Deputy Chair (who is also the chief executive officer).
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] ACMA collects revenue on behalf of the Australian Government through broadcasting, radiocommunications and telecommunications taxes, charges and license fees.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] It also collects revenue from price-based allocation of spectrum.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The corporate structure comprises four divisions – Communications Infrastructure, Content, Consumer and Citizen, Corporate and Research, and Legal Services.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] ACMA has responsibilities under four principal Acts – the Broadcasting Services Act 1992, the Telecommunications Act 1997, the Telecommunications (Consumer Protection and Service Standards) Act 1999 and the Radiocommunications Act 1992.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] There are another 22 Acts to which the agency responds in such areas as spam, the Do Not Call Register and interactive gambling.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The ACMA also creates and administers more than 523 legislative instruments including radiocommunications, spam and telecommunications regulations; and license area plans for free-to-air broadcasters.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] ACMA's main offices are located in Canberra, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Communications convergence is the merging of the previously distinct services by which information is communicated – telephone, television (free-to-air and subscription) radio and newspapers – over digital platforms.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] ACMA also works with industry and citizens to solve new concerns and mitigate risks arising in the evolving networked society and information economy, recognizing that Australians are interacting with digital communications and content in changing ways.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Not only does ACMA address a wide range of responsibilities, it does so against a backdrop of rapid change.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Moreover, there are new platforms, applications, business models, value chains and forms of social interaction available with more to come in what is a dynamic, innovative environment.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Other challenges for regulators include cross-jurisdictional issues and the need for engagement and collaboration with stakeholders locally, regionally and internationally.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] ACMA has developed a 'converged communications regulator' framework which seeks to bring to the global discussion a 'common ground' to deliver outcomes in the public interest.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The four cornerstone parts to the framework, each divided into two sub-streams, are outlined below along with the main functions of ACMA under each task.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The ACMA administers a complaints mechanism for Australian residents and law enforcement agencies to report prohibited online content, including child sexual abuse material.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Within the scheme, which operates under Schedules 5 and 7 of the Broadcasting Services Act 1992, content is assessed with reference to the same criteria within the National Classification Scheme that applies to films and computer games in Australia.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The ACMA Hotline is one of a global network of international bodies within INHOPE – the International Association of Internet Hotlines that exchange information on child abuse images, pinpointing the hosting countries to help eradicate them from the web.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] INHOPE consists of 44 members in 38 countries, with members including the Internet Watch Foundation (UK), the National Centre for Missing and Exploited Children (USA), Cyberia (Canada), Friendly Runlet Foundation (Russian Federation) and the Internet Hotline Center Japan.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] All potentially illegal content is reported by the ACMA to law enforcement in Australia, or, in the case of child sexual abuse material hosted overseas, through INHOPE for rapid police notification and take-down in the host country.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The ACMA publishes comprehensive statistics and information about the ACMA Hotline on its website.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The majority of investigations the ACMA conducts concern online child sexual abuse material.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Complaints to the ACMA Hotline are usually made via a webform on the ACMA's website.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] During National Child Protection Week 2013, the ACMA Hotline conducted 418 investigations involving over 4,700 images of abused children to Australian police agencies or through the INHOPE international network for action overseas.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] During the week, the ACMA announced it is now working more closely with CrimeStoppers in Australia to make it easier to report illegal online content.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The ACMA's online role is not connected to ISP blocking 'worst of the worst' child abuse material, which was operated by ISPs and the Australian Federal Police.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] In July 2015, this function moved to the Office of the Children's safety Commissioner.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The scheme has been in operation since May 2007.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Since mid-2013, Salmat has managed the Register on behalf of ACMA.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] ACMA is responsible for enforcing the Spam Act 2003 which prohibits the sending of unsolicited commercial electronic messages with an Australian link.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] A message has an Australian link if it originates, or was authorised, in Australia, or if the message was accessed in Australia.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Anyone who sends commercial email, SMS, or instant messages must ensure that the message is sent with consent, contains sender identification and contact information and includes a functional unsubscribe facility.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Members of the public are able to make complaints and reports about commercial electronic messages to ACMA which may conduct formal investigations and take enforcement actions.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The ACMA developed the Australian Internet Security Initiative (AISI) to help address the problem of computers being compromised by the surreptitious installation of malicious software (malware).
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] 'Malware' enables a computer to be controlled remotely for illegal and harmful activities without the owner's knowledge.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The Telecommunications Sector Security Reform (TSSR) commenced on 18 September 2018.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] In 2000, a legislative framework for online content regulation was established by adding a new schedule (schedule 5) to the Broadcasting Services Act 1992.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The Australian Broadcasting Authority was responsible for managing and enforcing the framework, and this responsibility passed to ACMA in 2005.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The key element to the framework was the establishment of a complaints mechanism under Part 4 of the Schedule.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Members of the public could complain to ACMA about offensive material online, ACMA could investigate, and then notify Internet service providers to prevent access to prohibited content.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The framework also permitted ACMA to initiate an 'own-motion' investigation into potentially prohibited content.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The framework was designed to be consistent with the national classifications system (the Code and Classification Guidelines established by the Classification (Publications, Films and Computer Games) Act 1995).
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Through this mechanism of establishing what content is prohibited or possibly prohibited, ACMA effectively creates a "blacklist" of content to which Internet service providers must deny users access.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] This framework was amended further in 2007 by the Communications Legislation Amendment (Content Services) Act (2007) as Schedule 5 only applied to stored content made available over the Internet but did not apply easily to "ephemeral" content such as streamed material.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] A new schedule (schedule 7) was introduced to regulate this content consistently with the national classifications system.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] On 10 March 2009, the ACMA issued an "interim link-deletion notice" to Bulletproof Networks, an Australian web-hosting company, on the grounds that Whirlpool, a customer of Bulletproof Networks, posted a link to a blacklisted, anti-abortion web site.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] There was a controversy that the material hosted by Whirlpool was the response notification from ACMA stating that the website had been blacklisted (the notice included the address of the website that had been blacklisted).
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] On 19 March 2009 it was reported that the ACMA's blacklist of banned sites had been leaked online, and had been published by WikiLeaks.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Julian Assange, founder of WikiLeaks, obtained the blacklist after the ACMA blocked several WikiLeaks pages following their publication of the Danish blacklist.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Assange said that "This week saw Australia joining China and the United Arab Emirates as the only countries censoring WikiLeaks." Three lists purporting to be from the ACMA were published online over a seven-day period.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] The leaked list, which was reported to have been obtained from a manufacturer of internet filtering software, contained 2395 sites.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Colin Jacobs, spokesman for lobby group Electronic Frontiers Australia, said that there was no mechanism for a site operator to know they got onto the list or to request to be removed from it.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Australia's Communications Minister, Stephen Conroy later blamed the addition of the dentist's website to the blacklist on the "Russian mob".
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Associate professor Bjorn Landfeldt of the University of Sydney said that the leaked list "constitutes a condensed encyclopedia of depravity and potentially very dangerous material".
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Stephen Conroy said the list was not the real blacklist and described its leak and publication as "grossly irresponsible" and that it undermined efforts to improve "cyber safety".
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] He said that ACMA was investigating the incident and considering a range of possible actions including referral to the Australian Federal Police, and that Australians involved in making the content available would be at "serious risk of criminal prosecution".
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] He added that the ACMA advised that there were URLs on the leaked list that had never been the subject of a complaint or ACMA investigation, and had never been included on the ACMA blacklist.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] He was backed up by ISP Tech 2U, one of six ISPs involved in filtering technology trials.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Conroy later claimed the leaked blacklist published on WikiLeaks closely resembled the official blacklist, admitting that the latest list (dated 18 March) "seemed to be close" to ACMA's current blacklist.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] In an estimates hearing of the Australian Federal Government on 25 May 2009 it was revealed that the leak was taken so seriously that it was referred to the Australian Federal Police for investigation.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] It was further stated that distribution of further updates to the list have been withheld until recipients can improve their security.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] Nerida O'Laughlin of the ACMA confirmed that the list has been reviewed and as of 30 April consists of 997 URLs.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] In 2021, Schedules 5 and 7 of the Broadcasting Services Act 1992 were repealed as part of the enactment of the Online Safety Act 2021.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-communications-media-authority] This Act established the eSafety Commissioner (section 26) and, under part 3 of the Act, gave the Commissioner responsibility for managing and enforcing the online content scheme (part 9).
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The **Australian Competition and Consumer Commission** (**ACCC**) is the chief competition regulator of the Government of Australia, located within the Department of the Treasury.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] It was established in 1995 with the amalgamation of the Australian Trade Practices Commission and the Prices Surveillance Authority to administer the *Trade Practices Act 1974*, which was replaced by the *Competition and Consumer Act 2010* on 1 January 2011.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The ACCC's mandate is to protect consumer rights, business rights and obligations, to perform industry regulation and price monitoring, and to prevent illegal anti-competitive behaviour.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The ACCC's deeper origins are found in the *Restrictive Trade Practices Act 1965* of Sir Garfield Barwick, Attorney-General in the Liberal government of Sir Robert Menzies in 1965.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] Though recognised as a failure, Barwick's legislation established in Australian law "the principle of legislative coverage of trade practices".
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] Lionel Murphy, the Attorney-General in the Whitlam Labor government, solicited the advice of the economist and business commentator, Professor Ted Wheelwright.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] In April 1973, Wheelwright produced a report for Murphy which became the blueprint of new legislation.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] He recommended, among other things, that the Act be clearly focused on protecting the consumer.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] Murphy is acknowledged as having completely changed the previous approach regarding trade practices in Australia.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] Though the Act included substantial penalties, Murphy's initiative received very little opposition in the Parliament or the business community.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The ACCC administers the Competition and Consumer Act, and has standing to take action in the Federal Court of Australia to enforce its provision.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The Competition and Consumer Act contains a broad range of provisions, such as provisions on anti-competitive conduct, the Australian Consumer Law and regulation of telecommunications and energy industries.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The ACCC, under the Act, also regulates certain industries by providing access to national infrastructure.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The ACCC also has an educative role and seeks to educate both consumers and businesses as to their rights and responsibilities under the Act.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The Australian Energy Regulator is a constituent but separate part of the ACCC and is responsible for economic energy regulation.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] It shares staff and premises with the ACCC, but has a separate board, although at least one board member must also be a Commissioner at the ACCC.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] In most cases the spirit of the Act, and thus the actions of the ACCC, favours neither consumer nor supplier, but strives to achieve a competitive market without artificial restrictions.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] For example, refusal to deal – a producer refusing to supply a potential retailer or customer with a product – is not itself illegal unless the action would have an anti-competitive effect on the market as a whole.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The ACCC brings court action against companies that breach the Competition and Consumer Act 2010, which can result in the application of fines and other penalties.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The maximum fine for a corporation is calculated as the larger of: $50,000,000; or three times the value of the illegal benefit; or (if the value of the benefit cannot be ascertained) 30% of turnover for the preceding 12 months.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] Individuals may be fined up to $2,500,000 under the Competition and Consumer Act for offences such as price fixing or participation in a cartel.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The ACCC also has power to accept, on its own behalf, court enforceable undertakings under section 87B of the Competition and Consumer Act.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] Such undertakings may include a wide range of remedies to the conduct.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] A range of other remedies can be ordered by the court.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] For example, companies are frequently forced to publish retractions of false advertising claims in national newspapers and at their places of business.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] Companies found in breach of the CCA are usually bound to implement a compliance program to ensure future compliance with the Act.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] In regard to its role of safeguarding consumer rights, there has been occasional criticism of the ACCC for being "all-talk-no-action".
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] This criticism is most likely due to the inherent difficulty in obtaining sufficient evidence to prove breaches of the restrictive trade practices provisions of the Competition and Consumer Act.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The ACCC has exercised its authority in a number of retail areas, including fining retailer Target for false advertising and Woolworths (including some Safeway-branded supermarkets in Victoria) for anti-competitive liquor deals.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] In 2008, the ACCC published findings of its inquiry into the competitiveness of retail prices for groceries in Australia.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The report found that the Australian supermarket sector is "workably competitive", but price competition is limited by barriers to entry and a lack of incentive for the two major players, Coles and Woolworths, to compete on price.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The report also noted that Coles and Woolworths engage in deliberate strategies designed to ensure they maintain exclusive access to prime sites such as shopping centres to prevent centre managers leasing space to competing supermarkets.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] In September 2009, the ACCC reached agreement with Coles and Woolworths to phase out restrictive lease agreements.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The ACCC has enforced the law against producers of quack devices with medical claims like Power Balance.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] It won a case on 24 March 2016 against Valve for failing to provide refunds for faulty products, and making representations that domestic consumer guarantees did not apply to purchases using the Steam client.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The ACCC maintains a website listing all Australian product recalls.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-competition-consumer-commission] The News Media Bargaining Code (NMBC, or News Media and Digital Platforms Mandatory Bargaining Code) is a law designed to have large technology platforms that operate in Australia pay local news publishers for the news content made available or linked on their platforms.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] The **Australian Prudential Regulation Authority** (**APRA**) is a statutory authority of the Australian Government and the prudential regulator of the Australian financial services industry.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] APRA was established on 1 July 1998 in response to the recommendations of the Wallis Inquiry.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] APRA's authority and scope is determined pursuant to the *Australian Prudential Regulation Authority Act, 1998* (Cth).
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] It oversees banks, credit unions, building societies, friendly societies, general insurance, health insurance, reinsurance, and life insurance companies, and most members of the superannuation industry.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] It ensures that these institutions keep their financial promises; that is, that they will remain financially sound and able to meet their obligations to depositors, fund members and policy holders.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] APRA currently supervises institutions holding A$8.6 trillion in assets for Australian depositors, policyholders and superannuation fund members.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] APRA is largely funded by levies on the financial institutions that it supervises.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] APRA is governed by an Executive Group, usually consisting of four people.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] The current Chair of APRA is John Lonsdale and the Deputy Chair is Margaret Cole.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] Suzanne Smith and Therese McCarthy Hockey are additional APRA Members.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] The Insurance and Superannuation Commission (ISC) was formally established on 23 November 1987, following the proclamation of the Insurance and Superannuation Commissioner Act 1987.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] It was constructed from the Superannuation Division of Treasury, The Office of the General Insurance Commissioner, The Office of Life Insurance Commissioner, and The Office of the Australian Government Actuary.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] The commission was based at the Australian Automobile Association Building, Canberra and also had offices in Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] The Insurance and Superannuation Commission was absorbed into the Australian Prudential Regulation Authority on 1 July 1998.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] At the time, the regulators of the Australian financial services industry were based on the institutions and not the regulatory function.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] APRA's predecessor regulators were the Insurance and Superannuation Commission, the Reserve Bank of Australia and the Australian Financial Institutions Commission (AFIC).
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] The Wallis Inquiry recommended a new structure.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] The role of the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) was amended to deal with monetary policy and systemic stability with the Payments System Board considering payments systems regulation.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] The role of the Australian Prudential Regulation Commission (later to become APRA) was amended to deal with prudential regulation of authorised deposit-taking institutions (ADIs), life and general insurance, and superannuation including Industry superannuation.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] The Corporations and Financial Services Commission was renamed and its role expanded as the Australian Securities and Investments Commission (ASIC) to deal with market integrity, consumer protection and corporations.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] APRA was established on 1 July 1998 under the *Australian Prudential Regulation Authority Act 1998*.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] APRA became prominent in the collapse of HIH Insurance in 2001 and for its investigation into the National Australia Bank foreign currency deal scandal in 2004.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] APRA took over the previous role of the Private Health Insurance Administration Council in July 2015.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] In 2018, Peter Harris, the chair of the Productivity Commission, was critical of the role of APRA in limiting price competition in banking.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] Representatives of APRA appeared before the Royal Commission into Misconduct in the Banking, Superannuation and Financial Services Industry during 2018.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] In 2018, APRA created the restricted authorised deposit-taking institution (RADI) licensing framework to encourage new entrants and competition to the existing banking system.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] In 2025, APRA has again increased the cash reserve requirement for ANZ Group, raising it to A$1 billion from A$750 million, citing continued failures in managing non-financial risks.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] APRA said these issues may extend beyond the trading desk and that ANZ’s current risk management improvements are insufficient.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] ANZ said in a separate statement that it had accepted all recommendations of the review, and was taking immediate actions in response to the review and the undertaking with APRA.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] Mark Evans, currently head of Singapore, Southeast Asia, India and the Middle East, will take up the new role of group head of non-financial risk program.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] APRA establishes prudential standards with which regulated institutions must comply.
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] It also creates and maintains *Prudential Practice Guides* (PPGs) to provide guidance on APRA's view of "sound practice" in particular areas for specific industries, as well as areas common to most APRA-regulated entities ("cross-industry guides").
[src:regulatory-compliance/australian-prudential-regulation-authority] PPGs frequently discuss statutory requirements from legislation, regulations or APRA's prudential standards, but do not themselves create enforceable requirements.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In general, **compliance** means conforming to a rule, such as a specification, policy, standard or law.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Compliance has traditionally been explained by reference to deterrence theory, according to which punishing a behavior will decrease the violations both by the wrongdoer (specific deterrence) and by others (general deterrence).
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] This view has been supported by economic theory, which has framed punishment in terms of costs and has explained compliance in terms of a cost-benefit equilibrium (Becker 1968).
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] However, psychological research on motivation provides an alternative view: granting rewards (Deci, Koestner and Ryan, 1999) or imposing fines (Gneezy Rustichini 2000) for a certain behavior is a form of extrinsic motivation that weakens intrinsic motivation and ultimately undermines compliance.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Regulations and accrediting organizations vary among fields, with examples such as PCI-DSS and GLBA in the financial industry, FISMA for U.S. federal agencies, HACCP for the food and beverage industry, and the Joint Commission and HIPAA in healthcare.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In some cases other compliance frameworks (such as COBIT) or even standards (NIST) inform on how to comply with regulations.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Some organizations keep compliance data—all data belonging or pertaining to the enterprise or included in the law, which can be used for the purpose of implementing or validating compliance—in a separate store for meeting reporting requirements.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Compliance software is increasingly being implemented to help companies manage their compliance data more efficiently.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] This store may include calculations, data transfers, and audit trails.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The ISO also produces international standards such as ISO/IEC 27002 to help organizations meet regulatory compliance with their security management and assurance best practices.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Some local or international specialized organizations such as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) also develop standards and regulation codes.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] They thereby provide a wide range of rules and directives to ensure compliance of the products to safety, security or design standards.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance varies not only by industry but often by location.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The financial, research, and pharmaceutical regulatory structures in one country, for example, may be similar but with particularly different nuances in another country.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] These similarities and differences are often a product "of reactions to the changing objectives and requirements in different countries, industries, and policy contexts".
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] These regulators help to ensure financial institutes meet their promises, that transactional information is well documented, and that competition is fair while protecting consumers.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Australian organisations seeking to remain compliant with various regulations may turn to AS ISO 19600:2015 (which supersedes AS 3806-2006).
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] This standard helps organisations with compliance management, placing "emphasis on the organisational elements that are required to support compliance" while also recognizing the need for continual improvement.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In Canada, federal regulation of deposits, insurance, and superannuation is governed by two independent bodies: the OSFI through the Bank Act, and FINTRAC, mandated by the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act, 2001 (PCMLTFA).
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] These groups protect consumers, regulate how risk is controlled and managed, and investigate illegal action such as money laundering and terrorist financing.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] On a provincial level, each province maintain individuals laws and agencies.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Unlike any other major federation, Canada does not have a securities regulatory authority at the federal government level.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The provincial and territorial regulators work together to coordinate and harmonize regulation of the Canadian capital markets through the Canadian Securities Administrators (CSA).
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Other key regulators in Canada include the Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) for food safety, animal health, and plant health; Health Canada for public health; and Environment and Climate Change Canada for environment and sustainable energy.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] For more industry specific guidance, e.g., financial institutions, Canada's E-13 Regulatory Compliance Management provides specific compliance risk management tactics.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance in the European Union (EU) is governed by a harmonized legal framework designed to ensure consistency across member states while allowing for national implementation.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] EU compliance regulations cover various industries, including consumer product safety, financial services, environmental protection, and data privacy.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The General Product Safety Regulation (GPSR) establishes a unified safety framework for consumer products across the EU, requiring manufacturers to conduct risk assessments, maintain traceability documentation, and meet safety compliance standards before placing products on the market.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The GPSR applies to all consumer products made available in the EU unless covered by sector-specific regulations, such as medical devices or food products.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The regulation extends to products sold through e-commerce platforms, requiring online marketplaces to ensure that only compliant products are listed.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Fulfillment service providers are also included as economic operators, making them responsible for product safety compliance in certain cases.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] For business compliance, the EU’s regulatory approach is guided by the New Legislative Framework (NLF) and various sector-specific directives and regulations.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Businesses must comply with EU product conformity assessments and affix the CE marking to indicate compliance with essential safety and performance standards.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Financial compliance is enforced through regulations such as the Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID II) and the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which set strict requirements for financial transparency, consumer protection, and data security.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The EU Legislation Compliance framework ensures that organizations operate within the legal boundaries of EU directives, helping public and private entities manage regulatory risks efficiently.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Companies operating in the EU must stay updated on evolving compliance requirements, as non-compliance can lead to fines, product recalls, or restrictions on market access.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The financial sector in the Netherlands is heavily regulated.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The Dutch Central Bank (De Nederlandsche Bank N.V.) is the prudential regulator while the Netherlands Authority for Financial Markets (AFM) is the regulator for behavioral supervision of financial institutions and markets.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In India, compliance regulation takes place across three strata: Central, State, and Local regulation.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] India veers towards central regulation, especially of financial organizations and foreign funds.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Compliance regulations vary based on the industry segment in addition to the geographical mix.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Most regulation comes in the following broad categories: economic regulation, regulation in the public interest, and environmental regulation.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] India has also been characterized by poor compliance - reports suggest that only around 65% of companies are fully compliant to norms.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The Monetary Authority of Singapore is Singapore's central bank and financial regulatory authority.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] It administers the various statutes pertaining to money, banking, insurance, securities and the financial sector in general, as well as currency issuance.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] There is considerable regulation in the United Kingdom, some of which is derived from European Union legislation.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Various areas are policed by different bodies, such as the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), Environment Agency, Scottish Environment Protection Agency, Information Commissioner's Office, Care Quality Commission, and others: see List of regulators in the United Kingdom.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Important compliance issues for all organizations large and small include the Data Protection Act 2018 and, for the public sector, Freedom of Information Act 2000.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Corporate scandals and breakdowns such as the Enron case of reputational risk in 2001 have increased calls for stronger compliance and regulations, particularly for publicly listed companies.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) is an agency of the United States Department of the Treasury under the auspices of the Under Secretary of the Treasury for Terrorism and Financial Intelligence.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] OFAC administers and enforces economic and trade sanctions based on U.S. foreign policy and national security goals against targeted foreign states, organizations, and individuals.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in the U.S. generally means compliance with laws and regulations.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] These laws and regulations can have criminal or civil penalties.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The definition of what constitutes an effective compliance plan has been elusive.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Most authors, however, continue to cite the guidance provided by the United States Sentencing Commission in Chapter 8 of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Small Business Administration re-launched Business.gov (later Business.USA.gov and finally SBA.Gov) which provides a single point of access to government services and information that help businesses comply with government regulations.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Department of Labor, Occupational Health and Safety Administration (OSHA) was created by Congress to assure safe and healthful working conditions for working men and women by setting and enforcing standards and by providing training, outreach, education, and assistance.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] OSHA implements laws and regulations regularly in the following areas, construction, maritime, agriculture, and recordkeeping.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The United States Department of Transportation also has various laws and regulations requiring that prime contractors when bidding on federally funded projects engage in good faith effort compliance, meaning they must document their outreach to certified disadvantaged business enterprises.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Data retention is a part of regulatory compliance that is proving to be a challenge in many instances.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The security that comes from compliance with industry regulations can seem contrary to maintaining user privacy.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Data retention laws and regulations ask data owners and other service providers to retain extensive records of user activity beyond the time necessary for normal business operations.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] These requirements have been called into question by privacy rights advocates.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in this area is becoming very difficult.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Laws like the CAN-SPAM Act and Fair Credit Reporting Act in the U.S. require that businesses give people the right to be forgotten.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In other words, they must remove individuals from marketing lists if it is requested, tell them when and why they might share personal information with a third party, or at least ask permission before sharing that data.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Now, with new laws coming out that demand longer data retention despite the individual’s desires, it can create some real difficulties.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Money laundering and terrorist financing pose significant threats to the integrity of the financial system and national security.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] To combat these threats, the EU has adopted a risk-based approach to Anti-Money Laundering and Combating the Financing of Terrorism (AML/CFT) that relies on cooperation and coordination between EU and national authorities.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] In this context, risk-based regulation refers to the approach of identifying and assessing potential risks of money laundering and terrorist financing and implementing regulatory measures proportional to those risks.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] However, the shared enforcement powers between EU and national authorities in the implementation and enforcement of AML/CFT regulations can create legal implications and challenges.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] The potential for inconsistent application of AML regulations across different jurisdictions can create regulatory arbitrage and undermine the effectiveness of AML efforts.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Additionally, a lack of clear and consistent legal frameworks defining the roles and responsibilities of EU and national authorities in AML enforcement can lead to situations where accountability is difficult to establish.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Corporate Governance Code (formerly the Combined Code) is issued by the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) and "sets standards of good practice in relation to board leadership and effectiveness, remuneration, accountability, and relations with shareholders".
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] All companies with a Premium Listing of equity shares in the U.K. are required under the Listing Rules to report on how they have applied the Combined Code in their annual report and accounts.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] It further demonstrates the relationship that subsists among shareholders, management, and the independent audit teams.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] Financial statements must be prepared using a particular set of rules and regulations hence the rationale behind allowing the companies to apply the provisions of company law, international financial reporting standards (IFRS), as well as the U.K. stock exchange rules as directed by the FCA.
[src:regulatory-compliance/regulatory-compliance] It is also possible that shareholders may not understand the figures as presented in the various financial statements, hence it is critical that the board should provide notes on accounting policies as well as other explanatory notes to help them understand the report better.
